title: For Sale:  Forehand & Wadsworth .32 Double Action SA/DA Top Break Revolver
location: Spring Lake Park, Minneapolis / St. Paul, Minnesota
postcontent: Forehand and Wadsworth Top Break .32 SA/DA Revolver in used condition. Chrome finish shows some exterior wear and pitting. Cylinder appears to be in working order. 3.25” barrel shows some rifling intact although there is some pitting as expected. Neat collectible revolver from the early 1900’s! $99 In 1871 Sullivan Forehand and Henry C. Wadsworth founded Forehand & Wadsworth from the remnants of Ethan Allen & Company after the death of their father-in-law, Ethan Allen.Wadsworth sold his share of the company to Forehand in 1890 in order to retire and the company was rebranded as Forehand Arms.The company was involved with a patent infringement lawsuit on behalf of one of their employees, John C. Howe, against the United States government. Howe had patented an ammunition cartridge in 1864 and the US government infringed upon this design in 1868 with the "Cup Anvil Cartridge" until the expiration of Howe's patent in 1881. Howe asked Forehand to bring a lawsuit against the government and eight years later the company won the suit on behalf of Howe with a judgement of $66,000. The lawsuit was not paid until after Howe's death and a few weeks before the death of Forehand in 1898. Forehand's sons ran the business for several years following the death of their father, but sold it in 1902 to Hopkins & Allen, who had been making Forehand Arms' revolvers under contract.The Original Lincoln Pawn & Jewelry of Spring Lake Park8480 Central Ave NESpring Lake Park, MN 55432www.LincolnPawnShop.com

It's a little embarrassing that it's only been shot that many times to be honest with you - Just a bone-headed matter of not tightening the gas block properly and waiting to find out until I got to the range. Since then, I haven't had the time to fire it at all and it has just sat in the safe collecting dust. I'd like to see someone else really enjoy it.For those of you not familiar with VSeven - it's kind of like the Gucci of rifles in a way - they make some of the finest parts in the industry and make them extremely lightweight - often times out of materials like titanium or lightened billet aluminum. The barrel comes from the wonderful folks over at JP Rifles and is their pencil profile 14.5 inch barrel with their fin-thing around it (shown in the picture without the handguard). I'm honestly not even sure what the fin thing does but it looks badass and supposedly keeps you from melting your hand on the forend, and also keeps such a small profile barrel more rigid while staying lightweight. Not sure - haven't shot it enough to see if that is indeed true. The parts in this build include:- VSeven enlightened billet lower and upper receiver- CMC 3.5 pound flat-faced trigger- V Seven Titanium BCG- AXTS Raptor Charging Handle- Battle Arms Development club foot stock thing- Tactical Paracord I weaved myself to make the Battle Arms stock more snag-free. I won't be offended if you just cut it off- VSeven Enlightened 13.5 inch handguard M-Lok- JP Rifles Pencil Profile 14.5 inch barrel with the fin thing- Battle Arms Development ultra-light gas block- Pinned and welded Seekins Precision Flash Hider to bring to the NFA-legal 16+inches- Magpul SL Pistol GripIf you have any questions let me know. Not really your average "Starter Rifle" unless you're the type of dude who drove a Mercedes in High School - which is cool too because Merc's are badass. Just sayin'Thanks for looking!

title: For Sale:  Extremely Rare Colt 1st Generation Buntline Revolver (C13534)
postcontent: Extremely Rare Colt 1st Generation Buntline Revolver. Made in 1893. This is a Frontier Six Shooter .44-40 caliber revolver with factory 12” barrel. Technically this is a carbine since the true Buntlines were in a certain serial number range and had a flat top. Gun letters as seen. It comes with a factory original skeleton stock. The vast majority of these are replacements and these stocks can fetch $10,000 or more just by themselves. This gun was factory refinished and has about 80% of the finish remaining. It was shipped to the Fletcher Jenks and Company in Detroit with only one gun in shipment indicating that this is the one gun in the shipment. We cannot stress enough how rare it is to find an original Buntline / Carbine 1st Generation Colt Single Action. This is the only Single Action in 44-40 with a 12” barrel. Beautiful gun and among the rarest things you could find in Single Action collecting!http://www.collectorsfirearms.com/extremely-rare-colt-1st-generation-buntline-revolver-c13534/
